"{\"uid\": \"nationalgeographic.com-history-article-phrygian-hat-cap-phyrge-olympic-mascot-paris\", \"noun_phrases\": [{\"sentence\": \"The Phrygian cap may be over 3,000 years old, and has ties to figures throughout history, from mythical King Midas to Paul Revere.\", \"from\": 0, \"to\": 130, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4, \"end\": 16, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 104, \"end\": 114, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.0693547300698964e-81, \"text\": \"King Midas\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\"}, {\"begin\": 118, \"end\": 129, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul_Revere\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.754317342928126e-36, \"text\": \"Paul Revere\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul_Revere\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul_Revere\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"ties\", \"from\": 54, \"to\": 58}, {\"ngram\": \"figures\", \"from\": 62, \"to\": 69}, {\"ngram\": \"history\", \"from\": 81, \"to\": 88}]}, {\"sentence\": \"When the first official Olympic mascot-a rainbow-hued dachshund named Waldi-debuted at the 1972 Olympic games in Munich, Germany, it became a popular symbol of both the international event and the host country.\", \"from\": 132, \"to\": 342, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 245, \"end\": 251, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Munich\", \"score\": 0.9999999999781721, \"rank\": 1.998047825020605e-11, \"text\": \"Munich\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Munich\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Munich\"}, {\"begin\": 253, \"end\": 260, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Germany\", \"score\": 0.999947130797596, \"rank\": 4.917400357657742e-05, \"text\": \"Germany\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Germany\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Germany\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Olympic mascot\", \"from\": 156, \"to\": 170}, {\"ngram\": \"a rainbow-hued dachshund\", \"from\": 171, \"to\": 195}, {\"ngram\": \"the 1972 Olympic games\", \"from\": 219, \"to\": 241}, {\"ngram\": \"a popular symbol\", \"from\": 272, \"to\": 288}, {\"ngram\": \"both the international event\", \"from\": 292, \"to\": 320}, {\"ngram\": \"the host country\", \"from\": 325, \"to\": 341}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Since then, most Olympic mascots have been colorful animal characters.\", \"from\": 343, \"to\": 413, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"most Olympic mascots\", \"from\": 355, \"to\": 375}, {\"ngram\": \"colorful animal characters\", \"from\": 386, \"to\": 412}]}, {\"sentence\": \"For the 2024 Summer Olympics, however, host country France has chosena hat with an almost unpronounceable name.\", \"from\": 414, \"to\": 525, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 466, \"end\": 472, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"score\": 0.5811869027373652, \"rank\": 0.7205538587745928, \"text\": \"France\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the 2024 Summer Olympics\", \"from\": 418, \"to\": 442}, {\"ngram\": \"chosena hat\", \"from\": 477, \"to\": 488}, {\"ngram\": \"an almost unpronounceable name\", \"from\": 494, \"to\": 524}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Smiley Phryge (pronounced, with French style, as \\\"Free-juh\\\") represents what's known as a Phrygian cap, based on similar caps worn by 18th-century French revolutionaries, who saw it as a symbol of freedom.\", \"from\": 527, \"to\": 732, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 527, \"end\": 533, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Smiley\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.0383649789657207e-20, \"text\": \"Smiley\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Smiley\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Smiley\"}, {\"begin\": 559, \"end\": 565, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_language\", \"score\": 0.999920448544597, \"rank\": 7.954427011545439e-05, \"text\": \"French\", \"types\": [\"Q315\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_language\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_language\"}, {\"begin\": 617, \"end\": 629, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 674, \"end\": 696, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_Revolution\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"French revolutionaries\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_Revolution\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_Revolution\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Free-juh\", \"from\": 577, \"to\": 585}, {\"ngram\": \"similar caps\", \"from\": 640, \"to\": 652}, {\"ngram\": \"a symbol\", \"from\": 712, \"to\": 720}, {\"ngram\": \"freedom\", \"from\": 724, \"to\": 731}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In Eugene Delacroix's paintingLiberty Leading the People, the allegorical figure of Liberty hoists the French flag while wearing such a cap, with its distinctive forward-facing tip.\", \"from\": 733, \"to\": 914, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 743, \"end\": 752, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Delacroix_metro_station\", \"score\": 0.8843596018891788, \"rank\": 0.1306623545048451, \"text\": \"Delacroix\", \"types\": [\"Q719456\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Delacroix_metro_station\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Delacroix_metro_station\"}, {\"begin\": 836, \"end\": 847, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flag_of_France\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"French flag\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flag_of_France\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flag_of_France\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the People\", \"from\": 779, \"to\": 789}, {\"ngram\": \"the allegorical figure\", \"from\": 791, \"to\": 813}, {\"ngram\": \"such a cap\", \"from\": 862, \"to\": 872}, {\"ngram\": \"its distinctive forward-facing tip\", \"from\": 879, \"to\": 913}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But while France's Phryge is now canonized as an Olympic mascot (a fellow Phyrge represents the Paralympics), the origin of the cap goes back thousands of years, making appearances in the Trojan War, the legend of King Midas, and even the American Revolution.\", \"from\": 916, \"to\": 1175, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 926, \"end\": 932, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"score\": 0.5811869027373652, \"rank\": 0.7205538587745928, \"text\": \"France\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"an Olympic mascot\", \"from\": 962, \"to\": 979}, {\"ngram\": \"a fellow Phyrge\", \"from\": 981, \"to\": 996}, {\"ngram\": \"the Paralympics\", \"from\": 1008, \"to\": 1023}, {\"ngram\": \"the origin\", \"from\": 1026, \"to\": 1036}, {\"ngram\": \"the cap\", \"from\": 1040, \"to\": 1047}, {\"ngram\": \"years\", \"from\": 1071, \"to\": 1076}, {\"ngram\": \"appearances\", \"from\": 1085, \"to\": 1096}, {\"ngram\": \"the Trojan War\", \"from\": 1100, \"to\": 1114}, {\"ngram\": \"the legend\", \"from\": 1116, \"to\": 1126}, {\"ngram\": \"King Midas\", \"from\": 1130, \"to\": 1140}, {\"ngram\": \"even the American Revolution\", \"from\": 1146, \"to\": 1174}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The cap gets its name from Phrygia, an ancient kingdom located in what is now central Turkey.\", \"from\": 1177, \"to\": 1270, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1263, \"end\": 1269, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ottoman_Empire\", \"score\": 0.9999748198157012, \"rank\": 2.5180818385210785e-05, \"text\": \"Turkey\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ottoman_Empire\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ottoman_Empire\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The cap\", \"from\": 1177, \"to\": 1184}, {\"ngram\": \"its name\", \"from\": 1190, \"to\": 1198}, {\"ngram\": \"Phrygia\", \"from\": 1204, \"to\": 1211}, {\"ngram\": \"an ancient kingdom\", \"from\": 1213, \"to\": 1231}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Researchers think the Phrygians migrated there from the Balkans around 1200 B.C.\", \"from\": 1271, \"to\": 1351, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1293, \"end\": 1302, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.5536912880741724e-45, \"text\": \"Phrygians\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\"}, {\"begin\": 1347, \"end\": 1351, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 8.657969702219868e-24, \"text\": \"B.C.\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Researchers\", \"from\": 1271, \"to\": 1282}, {\"ngram\": \"the Balkans\", \"from\": 1323, \"to\": 1334}]}, {\"sentence\": \"and built their capital at thesite of Gordion.\", \"from\": 1352, \"to\": 1398, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1390, \"end\": 1397, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.4787674576526256e-49, \"text\": \"Gordion\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"their capital\", \"from\": 1362, \"to\": 1375}, {\"ngram\": \"thesite\", \"from\": 1379, \"to\": 1386}]}, {\"sentence\": \"And while most people are unfamiliar with the Phrygians, they feature prominently in stories still told today: The legendary king Midas was cursed to turn everything into gold, but archaeologists think Midas was a real-and very wealthy-Phrygian king who ruled in the eighth century B.C.\", \"from\": 1400, \"to\": 1686, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1446, \"end\": 1455, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.5536912880741724e-45, \"text\": \"Phrygians\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\"}, {\"begin\": 1525, \"end\": 1535, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.0693547300698964e-81, \"text\": \"king Midas\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\"}, {\"begin\": 1602, \"end\": 1607, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 6.044177594381728e-66, \"text\": \"Midas\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\"}, {\"begin\": 1682, \"end\": 1686, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 8.657969702219868e-24, \"text\": \"B.C.\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"most people\", \"from\": 1410, \"to\": 1421}, {\"ngram\": \"stories\", \"from\": 1485, \"to\": 1492}, {\"ngram\": \"everything\", \"from\": 1555, \"to\": 1565}, {\"ngram\": \"gold\", \"from\": 1571, \"to\": 1575}, {\"ngram\": \"archaeologists\", \"from\": 1581, \"to\": 1595}, {\"ngram\": \"a real-and very wealthy-Phrygian king\", \"from\": 1612, \"to\": 1649}]}, {\"sentence\": \"University of Pennsylvania archaeologistBrian Rose, who has led excavations at Gordion since 2013, believes the myth of Midas' \\\"Golden Touch\\\" may have originated with the clothing of Phrygian aristocrats, who wore garments dyed with a particular pigment to give them a golden sheen.\", \"from\": 1688, \"to\": 1970, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1767, \"end\": 1774, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.4787674576526256e-49, \"text\": \"Gordion\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\"}, {\"begin\": 1808, \"end\": 1813, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 6.044177594381728e-66, \"text\": \"Midas\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\"}, {\"begin\": 1871, \"end\": 1879, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"score\": 0.9999805356599458, \"rank\": 1.946471910855244e-05, \"text\": \"Phrygian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Pennsylvania\", \"from\": 1702, \"to\": 1714}, {\"ngram\": \"excavations\", \"from\": 1752, \"to\": 1763}, {\"ngram\": \"the myth\", \"from\": 1796, \"to\": 1804}, {\"ngram\": \"the clothing\", \"from\": 1855, \"to\": 1867}, {\"ngram\": \"garments\", \"from\": 1902, \"to\": 1910}, {\"ngram\": \"a particular pigment\", \"from\": 1921, \"to\": 1941}, {\"ngram\": \"a golden sheen\", \"from\": 1955, \"to\": 1969}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The tens of thousands ofstunning artifacts recovered at Gordion, including vessels and jewelry of gold andfine wooden furniture, attest to the Phrygians' great-and very real-wealth.\", \"from\": 1971, \"to\": 2152, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2027, \"end\": 2034, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.4787674576526256e-49, \"text\": \"Gordion\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\"}, {\"begin\": 2114, \"end\": 2123, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.5536912880741724e-45, \"text\": \"Phrygians\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The tens of thousands\", \"from\": 1971, \"to\": 1992}, {\"ngram\": \"artifacts\", \"from\": 2004, \"to\": 2013}, {\"ngram\": \"vessels\", \"from\": 2046, \"to\": 2053}, {\"ngram\": \"jewelry\", \"from\": 2058, \"to\": 2065}, {\"ngram\": \"gold andfine wooden furniture\", \"from\": 2069, \"to\": 2098}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Then there is the Gordion Knot, an intricate tangle of rope said to have been tied by Midas' father Gordias (also a real person, for whom Gordion was named) and which was displayed in the capital's Temple of Zeus.\", \"from\": 2154, \"to\": 2367, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2172, \"end\": 2179, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.4787674576526256e-49, \"text\": \"Gordion\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\"}, {\"begin\": 2240, \"end\": 2245, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 6.044177594381728e-66, \"text\": \"Midas\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Midas\"}, {\"begin\": 2254, \"end\": 2261, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordias\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Gordias\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordias\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordias\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"an intricate tangle\", \"from\": 2186, \"to\": 2205}, {\"ngram\": \"rope\", \"from\": 2209, \"to\": 2213}, {\"ngram\": \"also a real person\", \"from\": 2263, \"to\": 2281}, {\"ngram\": \"Gordion\", \"from\": 2292, \"to\": 2299}, {\"ngram\": \"the capital's Temple\", \"from\": 2338, \"to\": 2358}, {\"ngram\": \"Zeus\", \"from\": 2362, \"to\": 2366}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Legend stipulated that only a person who untied it could rule over Asia, but the knot remained resolutely fastened until Alexander the Great visited Gordion in 333 B.C.\", \"from\": 2369, \"to\": 2537, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2533, \"end\": 2537, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 8.657969702219868e-24, \"text\": \"B.C.\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Legend\", \"from\": 2369, \"to\": 2375}, {\"ngram\": \"only a person\", \"from\": 2392, \"to\": 2405}, {\"ngram\": \"Asia\", \"from\": 2436, \"to\": 2440}, {\"ngram\": \"the knot\", \"from\": 2446, \"to\": 2454}, {\"ngram\": \"Alexander\", \"from\": 2490, \"to\": 2499}, {\"ngram\": \"the Great visited Gordion\", \"from\": 2500, \"to\": 2525}]}, {\"sentence\": \"and simply slashed it apart with his sword.\", \"from\": 2538, \"to\": 2581, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"his sword\", \"from\": 2571, \"to\": 2580}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The Phrygian cap (and future Olympic mascot) first appears in a carved depiction of a cavalryman found at Gordion and dating from the early ninth century B.C.\", \"from\": 2583, \"to\": 2741, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2587, \"end\": 2599, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 2689, \"end\": 2696, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.4787674576526256e-49, \"text\": \"Gordion\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gordion\"}, {\"begin\": 2737, \"end\": 2741, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 8.657969702219868e-24, \"text\": \"B.C.\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"future Olympic mascot\", \"from\": 2605, \"to\": 2626}, {\"ngram\": \"a carved depiction\", \"from\": 2645, \"to\": 2663}, {\"ngram\": \"a cavalryman\", \"from\": 2667, \"to\": 2679}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\\"That's the earliest visual reference we have,\\\" says Rose.\", \"from\": 2742, \"to\": 2800, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2795, \"end\": 2799, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rose\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.896356023736272e-14, \"text\": \"Rose\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rose\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Rose\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the earliest visual reference\", \"from\": 2750, \"to\": 2779}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Rose notes the ancient Greeks considered the Trojans in Homer'sIliadto be associates of the Phrygians-and theIliaditself records that Trojan queen Hecuba was the daughter of a Phrygian king.\", \"from\": 2802, \"to\": 2992, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2817, \"end\": 2831, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.7297776001416685e-31, \"text\": \"ancient Greeks\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\"}, {\"begin\": 2847, \"end\": 2854, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\", \"score\": 0.99993196239211, \"rank\": 6.80422375444736e-05, \"text\": \"Trojans\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\"}, {\"begin\": 2949, \"end\": 2955, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hecuba\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.447932973544492e-31, \"text\": \"Hecuba\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hecuba\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hecuba\"}, {\"begin\": 2978, \"end\": 2986, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"score\": 0.9999805356599458, \"rank\": 1.946471910855244e-05, \"text\": \"Phrygian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Rose\", \"from\": 2802, \"to\": 2806}, {\"ngram\": \"Homer'sIliadto\", \"from\": 2858, \"to\": 2872}, {\"ngram\": \"associates\", \"from\": 2876, \"to\": 2886}, {\"ngram\": \"the Phrygians\", \"from\": 2890, \"to\": 2903}, {\"ngram\": \"theIliaditself\", \"from\": 2908, \"to\": 2922}, {\"ngram\": \"the daughter\", \"from\": 2960, \"to\": 2972}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Mythical Troy was on the Anatolian coast, far from the Phrygian heartland, but the ancient Greek association may be evidence of Phrygian power.\", \"from\": 2994, \"to\": 3137, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3003, \"end\": 3007, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.310563279991094e-60, \"text\": \"Troy\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\"}, {\"begin\": 3019, \"end\": 3028, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anatolia\", \"score\": 0.9999999999995453, \"rank\": 3.3169438460267745e-13, \"text\": \"Anatolian\", \"types\": [\"Q23442\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anatolia\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anatolia\"}, {\"begin\": 3049, \"end\": 3057, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"score\": 0.9999805356599458, \"rank\": 1.946471910855244e-05, \"text\": \"Phrygian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\"}, {\"begin\": 3077, \"end\": 3090, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"score\": 0.9999995832864401, \"rank\": 4.086738797128752e-07, \"text\": \"ancient Greek\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\"}, {\"begin\": 3122, \"end\": 3130, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"score\": 0.9999805356599458, \"rank\": 1.946471910855244e-05, \"text\": \"Phrygian\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygians\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"evidence\", \"from\": 3110, \"to\": 3118}]}, {\"sentence\": \"A central character in theIliadis the Trojan prince Paris, who ultimately sparks the Trojan War when goddesses ask him to decide who was the most beautiful.\", \"from\": 3139, \"to\": 3295, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3191, \"end\": 3196, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 0.9999999999895408, \"rank\": 1.0578920792033917e-11, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"A central character\", \"from\": 3139, \"to\": 3158}, {\"ngram\": \"theIliadis\", \"from\": 3162, \"to\": 3172}, {\"ngram\": \"the Trojan War\", \"from\": 3220, \"to\": 3234}, {\"ngram\": \"goddesses\", \"from\": 3240, \"to\": 3249}]}, {\"sentence\": \"That scene-known as the Judgement of Paris-was a popular subject of ancient Greek artists.\", \"from\": 3296, \"to\": 3386, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3364, \"end\": 3377, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"score\": 0.9999995832864401, \"rank\": 4.086738797128752e-07, \"text\": \"ancient Greek\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greece\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the Judgement\", \"from\": 3316, \"to\": 3329}, {\"ngram\": \"Paris\", \"from\": 3333, \"to\": 3338}, {\"ngram\": \"a popular subject\", \"from\": 3343, \"to\": 3360}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Artistic depictions of the Trojan prince often featured him wearing a Phrygian cap, which was visual shorthand that he was not Greek, saysMargaret Miller, professor emerita of archaeology at Australia's University of Sydney.\", \"from\": 3388, \"to\": 3612, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3458, \"end\": 3470, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 3543, \"end\": 3560, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emeritus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.7619231073127575e-24, \"text\": \"professor emerita\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emeritus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emeritus\"}, {\"begin\": 3579, \"end\": 3588, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Australia\", \"score\": 0.9999999740662137, \"rank\": 1.678980610364555e-08, \"text\": \"Australia\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Australia\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Australia\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Artistic depictions\", \"from\": 3388, \"to\": 3407}, {\"ngram\": \"the Trojan prince\", \"from\": 3411, \"to\": 3428}, {\"ngram\": \"visual shorthand\", \"from\": 3482, \"to\": 3498}, {\"ngram\": \"saysMargaret Miller\", \"from\": 3522, \"to\": 3541}, {\"ngram\": \"archaeology\", \"from\": 3564, \"to\": 3575}, {\"ngram\": \"Sydney\", \"from\": 3605, \"to\": 3611}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Paris wears several different Phrygian caps in different artworks, one of which looks to be made from an animal skin-and Miller thinks this may have been the origin of the distinctive style, with the head or neck of an animal skin forming the cap's distinctive \\\"horn\\\" or forward-facing tip.\", \"from\": 3614, \"to\": 3904, \"entities\