, \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Greek_art\"}, {\"begin\": 4018, \"end\": 4026, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Achaemenid_Empire\", \"score\": 0.9999995861490735, \"rank\": 4.138506208623655e-07, \"text\": \"Persians\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Achaemenid_Empire\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Achaemenid_Empire\"}, {\"begin\": 4035, \"end\": 4040, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Medes\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.2796053078792578e-54, \"text\": \"Medes\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Medes\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Medes\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"a symbol\", \"from\": 3942, \"to\": 3950}, {\"ngram\": \"anyone\", \"from\": 3968, \"to\": 3974}, {\"ngram\": \"the Middle East\", \"from\": 3991, \"to\": 4006}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Much later it became associated with the Roman god Mithras, who supposedly originated in Persia.\", \"from\": 4042, \"to\": 4138, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4083, \"end\": 4092, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 7.75896877223737e-29, \"text\": \"Roman god\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\"}, {\"begin\": 4093, \"end\": 4100, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mithraism\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Mithras\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mithraism\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mithraism\"}, {\"begin\": 4131, \"end\": 4137, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Achaemenid_Empire\", \"score\": 0.9999993974372042, \"rank\": 6.025630803216779e-07, \"text\": \"Persia\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Achaemenid_Empire\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Achaemenid_Empire\"}], \"noun_phrases\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The Phrygian cap even became an emblem of Rome itself: according to Virgil'sAeneid, an epic poem written in the first century B.C., the Trojan hero Aeneas and his followers arrived in Italy after the Trojan War and founded the city of Alba Longa a few miles from the future site of Rome.\", \"from\": 4140, \"to\": 4427, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4144, \"end\": 4156, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 4182, \"end\": 4186, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.9999994414549033, \"rank\": 5.585453725674131e-07, \"text\": \"Rome\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}, {\"begin\": 4208, \"end\": 4214, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.4112422077948616e-44, \"text\": \"Virgil\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q36180\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Virgil\"}, {\"begin\": 4266, \"end\": 4270, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 8.657969702219868e-24, \"text\": \"B.C.\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anno_Domini\"}, {\"begin\": 4288, \"end\": 4294, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aeneas\", \"score\": 0.9999999980432221, \"rank\": 1.956675325845434e-09, \"text\": \"Aeneas\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aeneas\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aeneas\"}, {\"begin\": 4324, \"end\": 4329, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Italy\", \"score\": 0.9999989138433635, \"rank\": 1.0861575405737069e-06, \"text\": \"Italy\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Italy\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Italy\"}, {\"begin\": 4375, \"end\": 4385, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alba_Longa\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.36186919762154e-22, \"text\": \"Alba Longa\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alba_Longa\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alba_Longa\"}, {\"begin\": 4422, \"end\": 4426, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.9999994414549033, \"rank\": 5.585453725674131e-07, \"text\": \"Rome\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"an emblem\", \"from\": 4169, \"to\": 4178}, {\"ngram\": \"an epic poem\", \"from\": 4224, \"to\": 4236}, {\"ngram\": \"the Trojan hero\", \"from\": 4272, \"to\": 4287}, {\"ngram\": \"his followers\", \"from\": 4299, \"to\": 4312}, {\"ngram\": \"the Trojan War\", \"from\": 4336, \"to\": 4350}, {\"ngram\": \"the city\", \"from\": 4363, \"to\": 4371}, {\"ngram\": \"the future site\", \"from\": 4403, \"to\": 4418}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Because the mother of Rome's mythical founder Romulus was the daughter of Alba Longa's king, the Romans could claim descent from the Trojans, making the Phrygian cap a symbol of their foreign origins.\", \"from\": 4429, \"to\": 4629, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4451, \"end\": 4455, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.9999994414549033, \"rank\": 5.585453725674131e-07, \"text\": \"Rome\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}, {\"begin\": 4503, \"end\": 4513, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alba_Longa\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.36186919762154e-22, \"text\": \"Alba Longa\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alba_Longa\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Alba_Longa\"}, {\"begin\": 4526, \"end\": 4532, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.9999985004107987, \"rank\": 1.4995916657482653e-06, \"text\": \"Romans\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}, {\"begin\": 4562, \"end\": 4569, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\", \"score\": 0.99993196239211, \"rank\": 6.80422375444736e-05, \"text\": \"Trojans\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Troy\"}, {\"begin\": 4582, \"end\": 4594, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the mother\", \"from\": 4437, \"to\": 4447}, {\"ngram\": \"the daughter\", \"from\": 4487, \"to\": 4499}, {\"ngram\": \"descent\", \"from\": 4545, \"to\": 4552}, {\"ngram\": \"their foreign origins\", \"from\": 4607, \"to\": 4628}]}, {\"sentence\": \"After the end of the Roman Empire, however, the symbolism of the Phrygian cap becomes unclear.\", \"from\": 4631, \"to\": 4725, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4652, \"end\": 4664, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.9977302112090384, \"rank\": 0.0022749524527465067, \"text\": \"Roman Empire\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}, {\"begin\": 4696, \"end\": 4708, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the end\", \"from\": 4637, \"to\": 4644}, {\"ngram\": \"the symbolism\", \"from\": 4675, \"to\": 4688}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Roman art features another type of cap, a conical hat called thepileus, which was given to Roman slaves when they were freed and became a visual symbol of manumission, or freedom from slavery.\", \"from\": 4727, \"to\": 4919, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4727, \"end\": 4736, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.999999997888608, \"rank\": 2.1115098597526818e-09, \"text\": \"Roman art\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}, {\"begin\": 4818, \"end\": 4823, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"score\": 0.9997903413585435, \"rank\": 0.00020970197547798676, \"text\": \"Roman\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"another type\", \"from\": 4746, \"to\": 4758}, {\"ngram\": \"cap\", \"from\": 4762, \"to\": 4765}, {\"ngram\": \"a conical hat\", \"from\": 4767, \"to\": 4780}, {\"ngram\": \"thepileus\", \"from\": 4788, \"to\": 4797}, {\"ngram\": \"a visual symbol\", \"from\": 4863, \"to\": 4878}, {\"ngram\": \"manumission\", \"from\": 4882, \"to\": 4893}, {\"ngram\": \"freedom\", \"from\": 4898, \"to\": 4905}, {\"ngram\": \"slavery\", \"from\": 4911, \"to\": 4918}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Rose thinks ancient depictions of the pileus and the Phrygian cap became muddled in the 18thcentury, when revolutionary artists in Europe looked for symbols of freedom in Roman art.\", \"from\": 4921, \"to\": 5102, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4974, \"end\": 4986, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 5092, \"end\": 5101, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"score\": 0.999999997888608, \"rank\": 2.1115098597526818e-09, \"text\": \"Roman art\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Rome\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Rose\", \"from\": 4921, \"to\": 4925}, {\"ngram\": \"ancient depictions\", \"from\": 4933, \"to\": 4951}, {\"ngram\": \"the pileus\", \"from\": 4955, \"to\": 4965}, {\"ngram\": \"the 18thcentury\", \"from\": 5005, \"to\": 5020}, {\"ngram\": \"revolutionary artists\", \"from\": 5027, \"to\": 5048}, {\"ngram\": \"Europe\", \"from\": 5052, \"to\": 5058}, {\"ngram\": \"symbols\", \"from\": 5070, \"to\": 5077}, {\"ngram\": \"freedom\", \"from\": 5081, \"to\": 5088}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\\"When the French and British wanted to choose a cap of liberty from antiquity, they got it wrong,\\\" he says.\", \"from\": 5104, \"to\": 5211, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5125, \"end\": 5132, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain\", \"score\": 0.9597119357019704, \"rank\": 0.035358593443549, \"text\": \"British\", \"types\": [\"Q23442\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"a cap\", \"from\": 5150, \"to\": 5155}, {\"ngram\": \"liberty\", \"from\": 5159, \"to\": 5166}, {\"ngram\": \"antiquity\", \"from\": 5172, \"to\": 5181}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\\"They chose the Phrygian cap, which signified Middle East status, rather than the pileus, which signified liberty-and so the Phrygian cap came to be interpreted as a symbol of liberty.\\\"\", \"from\": 5212, \"to\": 5397, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5228, \"end\": 5240, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 5337, \"end\": 5349, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Middle East status\", \"from\": 5258, \"to\": 5276}, {\"ngram\": \"the pileus\", \"from\": 5290, \"to\": 5300}, {\"ngram\": \"liberty\", \"from\": 5318, \"to\": 5325}, {\"ngram\": \"a symbol\", \"from\": 5376, \"to\": 5384}, {\"ngram\": \"liberty\", \"from\": 5388, \"to\": 5395}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The \\\"liberty cap\\\" seems to have first appeared in pre-revolutionary America in the artwork of silversmith Paul Revere, who created several silver bowls in the 1760s that featured the Roman symbol, according toa 1987 articlebyYvonne Korshak, professor emerita of art history at New York's Adelphi University.\", \"from\": 5399, \"to\": 5706, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5505, \"end\": 5516, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul_Revere\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 4.754317342928126e-36, \"text\": \"Paul Revere\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul_Revere\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paul_Revere\"}, {\"begin\": 5582, \"end\": 5587, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"score\": 0.9997903413585435, \"rank\": 0.00020970197547798676, \"text\": \"Roman\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_mythology\"}, {\"begin\": 5640, \"end\": 5657, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emeritus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.7619231073127575e-24, \"text\": \"professor emerita\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emeritus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Emeritus\"}, {\"begin\": 5676, \"end\": 5684, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_York_City\", \"score\": 0.9999999978626875, \"rank\": 1.3957390300346446e-09, \"text\": \"New York\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_York_City\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_York_City\"}, {\"begin\": 5687, \"end\": 5705, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adelphi_University\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 7.460706758369933e-16, \"text\": \"Adelphi University\", \"types\": [\"Q43229\", \"Q3918\", \"Q24229398\", \"Q2385804\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adelphi_University\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Adelphi_University\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The \\\"liberty cap\", \"from\": 5399, \"to\": 5415}, {\"ngram\": \"pre-revolutionary America\", \"from\": 5449, \"to\": 5474}, {\"ngram\": \"the artwork\", \"from\": 5478, \"to\": 5489}, {\"ngram\": \"several silver bowls\", \"from\": 5530, \"to\": 5550}, {\"ngram\": \"the 1760s\", \"from\": 5554, \"to\": 5563}, {\"ngram\": \"toa\", \"from\": 5606, \"to\": 5609}, {\"ngram\": \"Korshak\", \"from\": 5631, \"to\": 5638}, {\"ngram\": \"art history\", \"from\": 5661, \"to\": 5672}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But Revere's depictions show a rounded cap rather than the forward-pointing Phrygian cap; in that form it became a common symbol of the American Revolution, appearing in paintings, in seals, and on flags.\", \"from\": 5708, \"to\": 5912, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5784, \"end\": 5796, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Revere's depictions\", \"from\": 5712, \"to\": 5731}, {\"ngram\": \"a rounded cap\", \"from\": 5737, \"to\": 5750}, {\"ngram\": \"that form\", \"from\": 5801, \"to\": 5810}, {\"ngram\": \"a common symbol\", \"from\": 5821, \"to\": 5836}, {\"ngram\": \"the American Revolution\", \"from\": 5840, \"to\": 5863}, {\"ngram\": \"paintings\", \"from\": 5878, \"to\": 5887}, {\"ngram\": \"seals\", \"from\": 5892, \"to\": 5897}, {\"ngram\": \"flags\", \"from\": 5906, \"to\": 5911}]}, {\"sentence\": \"A few years after the American Revolution, however, the Phrygian cap in its original shape became a symbol of revolutionary France-possibly because, as Korshak notes, it resembled the stocking caps commonly worn by French workers.\", \"from\": 5914, \"to\": 6144, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5970, \"end\": 5982, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Phrygian cap\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\"}, {\"begin\": 6129, \"end\": 6135, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_language\", \"score\": 0.999920448544597, \"rank\": 7.954427011545439e-05, \"text\": \"French\", \"types\": [\"Q315\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_language\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_language\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the American Revolution\", \"from\": 5932, \"to\": 5955}, {\"ngram\": \"its original shape\", \"from\": 5986, \"to\": 6004}, {\"ngram\": \"a symbol\", \"from\": 6012, \"to\": 6020}, {\"ngram\": \"revolutionary France\", \"from\": 6024, \"to\": 6044}, {\"ngram\": \"Korshak\", \"from\": 6066, \"to\": 6073}, {\"ngram\": \"the stocking caps\", \"from\": 6094, \"to\": 6111}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the course of the French Revolution, and for many years afterwards, the Phrygian cap appeared in paintings, illustrations, and onstatues of Marianne, the mythical personification of the French Republic that still decorate many town halls.\", \"from\": 6146, \"to\": 6387, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6221, \"end\": 6233, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phrygian_cap\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": 